text: This is a pretty complex question, but one main difference is that you cannot hedge in the underlying. I haven't seen anyone buy and sell a sunny day or the level of rainfall in a region over time. So if you're going to trade options on the weather, you're basically making a directional bet. That's point number one. So maybe weather derivatives are a little bit like the VIX, but they're not the VIX because they cannot be assembled from tradable financial instruments, however roughly. They're also a bit like fixed income in a way, because at least the historical quant models have a degree of mean reversion priced in. Maybe that's all broken nowadays, but historically they did. The classical model, I think, which was due to Vasechek, had explicit mean reversion and subsequent iterations also did. And the weather's a bit like that. It doesn't stray that far. Probably it's even more well-behaved than rates are. But by the same token... It's not tradable in the same way that rates are, because rates can be decomposed into forward rates and they can be spread cross-country, cross-credit, blah, blah, blah. And with the weather, you're kind of stuck. I mean, yes, you can trade Cincinnati versus Columbus. Fine. But it's much harder to assemble the payouts of the contract using other contracts. I analyzed it, tested how much variation the model produced relative to the real variation in the weather, and so on. So it's pretty different.
